<h1>Problem 145 - 2015 IMOSL, N3, N</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(m\) and \(n\) be positive integers such that \(m>n\). Define \(x_k=\frac{m+k}{n+k}\) for \(k=1,2,\ldots,n+1\). Prove that if all the numbers \(x_1,x_2,\ldots,x_{n+1}\) are integers, then \(x_1x_2\ldots x_{n+1}-1\) is divisible by an odd prime.</p>
